<H3> <TI>   Caldera Changes Cabinet In Midst of Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caldera Changes Cabinet In Midst of Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3005222094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1956 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA3005222094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Caracas</LOCATION>, 30 <DATE>May</DATE> (EFE) -- Today, Venezuelan President 
<PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON> carried out his first cabinet change, only 117 
days after the start of his government and in the mist of a 
profound economic crisis. 
  Caldera, who assumed the presidency on 2 <DATE>February</DATE>, appointed 
<PERSON>Alberto Poletto</PERSON>, <PERSON>Luis Carlos Palacios</PERSON>, <PERSON>Ciro Zaa</PERSON>, and <PERSON>Carlos 
Bernandez</PERSON> as ministers of Development, <ORGANIZATION>Central Office of 
Coordination</ORGANIZATION> and Planning [Cordiplan], <ORGANIZATION>Transport</ORGANIZATION> and 
Communication, and Venezuelan Investment Fund, respectively. 
  Caldera's restructuring of his cabinet has been interpreted 
by local political experts as a sign that the president is 
prepared to make a switch to an economic policy less populist 
than the one he proposed during the elections campaign and 
closer to the neoliberal policy implemented by former president 
<PERSON>Carlos Andres Perez</PERSON>. 
  Apparently, <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON>, who was one of the most severe critics 
of the free market policy promoted by <PERSON>Perez</PERSON>, has been unable to 
structure an economic formula out of the neoliberal guidelines. 
  <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> is living through a difficult economic situation, 
with a fiscal deficit estimated at more than <MONEY>$4.5 billion</MONEY>, a 
severe depreciation of the bolivar, and an explosive social 
situation fueled by a significant fall in the purchasing power 
of the people. 
  President <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> put <PERSON>Carlos Bernandez</PERSON> at the head of the 
organization in charge of privatizing state enterprises. 
Bernandez has always been linked to the local banking sector and 
he has been president of the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Venezuela</ORGANIZATION>, which is one of 
the most important banks in the country. Bernandez has offered 
to increase the privatization process. The local media has 
described his appointment as a victory for the financial sector, 
which was able to produce the departure of <PERSON>Abdon Vivas Teran</PERSON>, a 
politician very close to <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> and to his electoral offer for 
an economy with a human face, from the <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> Investment Fund. 
  Luis <PERSON>Carlos Palacios</PERSON>, the new Cordiplan minister, replaces 
<PERSON>Enzo del Bufalo</PERSON>, a dissonant voice in <LOCATION>Caldera</LOCATION>'s economic team. 
The new minister is closer to the free economy concepts that the 
<PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> administration apparently wants to adopt in this new 
phase. 
  Also, <PERSON>Alberto Poletto</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Trade 
Institute</ORGANIZATION>, will be development minister, which joins these 
departments to create the Industry and <ORGANIZATION>Commerce Ministry</ORGANIZATION>. 
  <PERSON>Ciro Zaa</PERSON> has been virtually forced to leave the <ORGANIZATION>Urban 
Development Ministry</ORGANIZATION> to take over the <ORGANIZATION>Transport and 
Communication Ministry</ORGANIZATION> vacated by <PERSON>Cesar Quintini</PERSON>, who was 
accused of maintaining an attitude of tolerance in multiple 
cases of corruption in his ministry. 
  Zaa will be replaced by <PERSON>Francisco Gonzalez</PERSON>, former president 
of the <ORGANIZATION>Urban Development</ORGANIZATION> fund. The responsibilities of Special 
Affairs Minister <PERSON>Pompeyo Marquez</PERSON> have been expanded and from now 
on he will also be responsible for the government's social 
programs. 

</TEXT>

