<H3> <TI>   President-Elect Caldera To Seek Suspension of VAT </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1301003594 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 1550 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1301003594 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FÊP=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President-elect <PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON> has insisted he will 
do everything possible to fulfill his electoral promise of 
suspending the controversial value-added tax [VAT]. 
  Caldera made this statement during a ceremony in his honor 
given by members of the <ORGANIZATION>Venezuelan Academy of Language</ORGANIZATION>. The 
ceremony was also attended by Venezuelan President <PERSON>Ramon J. 
Velasquez</PERSON> and other representatives from the Executive and 
Judicial Branches. <PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON> pointed out that as soon he 
starts his administration, he will present several proposals to 
the new parliament in an effort to make the VAT more just. 
  [Begin Caldera recording] I hope <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> will accept this. 
I have heard that some groups seem to be interested in learning 
more about my proposal and in accepting it in principle. I hope 
this will be the case. [end recording] 
  When consulted about the possibility of dismissing charges 
against the individuals involved in the massacre at <LOCATION>El Amparo</LOCATION>, 
the president-elect emphasized that the current government 
should be very careful in this respect. 

</TEXT>

