<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Unveils New Economic Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2804012094 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2804012094 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Ligia Moreno</PERSON> and <PERSON>Aneris Gonzalez</PERSON> from "The News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] [<PERSON>Moreno</PERSON>] The economic cabinet of President <PERSON>Rafael 
Caldera</PERSON> today announced the general strategy or guidelines of 
the economic plan to be implemented over the next five years. 
One of the highlights is that <ORGANIZATION>Venezuelan Petroleum</ORGANIZATION> will give <PERCENT>10 
percent</PERCENT> of its shares to its employees. Other major points 
include an emphasis on decentralization and private investments. 
Various sectors support the plan and think President <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> is 
on the right track. Time will tell, however, and we have to wait 
and see how the economic plan proposed by the <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> cabinet 
works. 
  [<PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>] It is worth mentioning that a large number of 
people from all sectors--namely, CTV [Confederation of 
Venezuelan Workers], Consecomercio [<ORGANIZATION>National Council of Commerce 
and Services</ORGANIZATION>], and <PERSON>Fedecamaras</PERSON> [<ORGANIZATION>Venezuelan Federation of 
Associations and Chambers of Commerce and Industry</ORGANIZATION>]--have 
gathered here at the Eurobuilding Hotel, as you can see your 
screen, to discuss and review the entire economic program. As 
you rightly pointed out, <LOCATION>Ligia</LOCATION>, the opening to private 
investment is one of the highlights of this strategy, and, in 
some way, it has grabbed the attention of all sectors of society. 

</TEXT>

