<H3> <TI>   Escovar Decries Existence of a `Rumor Mill' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Escovar Decries Existence of a `Rumor Mill' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1705153394 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 
16 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1705153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Vicente Briceno</PERSON> from the "Union Radio News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Interior Minister <PERSON>Ramon Escovar Salom</PERSON> has described 
the rumor mill as a criminal tactic to undermine the country's 
prestige abroad and the calm of citizens. He noted that the 
rumor mill has been active these past few days, and that even 
the health of President <PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON> has been questioned. 
  Escovar Salom gave no information on the inquiry conducted 
on 
a destabilization plan that includes this chain of rumors but 
termed them sources of unrest that seek to crumble the public's 
support for the Caldera government. He insisted this thing about 
the bogeyman is no cliche, but rather a conspiracy that involves 
a manipulation of the public and in no way is related to social 
unhappiness or protests over the water shortage. 
  [Begin <PERSON>Escovar Salom</PERSON> recording] Some people have made the 
absurd assertion that I want to explain the social crisis by 
blaming the bogeyman. I never said that. You are the first to 
know that is not so. You clearly heard what I said. The social 
crisis, which the government acknowledges, the economic crisis, 
and severe difficulties the country is experiencing is one 
matter. The manipulation and tactics by some sectors that have 
an interest in heightening the crisis and seeking other goals is 
another matter. That is what these sectors are trying to do. The 
events that took place over the weekend are clear proof that my 
remarks were serious and justified. I mean the rumor campaign. 
This rumor mill is criminal. I mean all these announcements of 
the future of the bolivar, devaluation, and alleged financial 
and fiscal measures the government is purportedly going to take. 
[end recording] 
  Commenting on the resignation of some members of the 
cabinet, 
<PERSON>Escovar Salom</PERSON> said any decision on the matter falls solely 
within the purview of President <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON>. On another matter, the 
<ORGANIZATION>Interior Minister</ORGANIZATION> commented on the border dispute between <LOCATION>Merida</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>Zulia States</LOCATION>. He noted this problem must be handled with 
utmost caution and prudence. 

</TEXT>

