<H3> <TI>   Venezuelan Ambassador Cited on Bilateral Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201011394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1801 GMT 21 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2201011394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Caracas</LOCATION>, 21 Jan (PL) -- Following a discussion with 
President-elect <PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON>, <PERSON>Gonzalo Garcia Bustillos</PERSON>, the 
Venezuelan ambassador in <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>, today stressed that relations 
between <LOCATION>Caracas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Havana</LOCATION> are excellent and friendly. 
  In statement to journalists, <PERSON>Garcia Bustillos</PERSON> said president 
<ORGANIZATION>Caldera's Government</ORGANIZATION> is willing to maintain friendly relations 
with <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>. 
  <PERSON>Garcia Bustillos</PERSON> also expressed his rejection of the 
economic 
blockade the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has maintained against <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION> for three 
decades, and he said measures of this sort should not be 
implemented at this time. 
  <PERSON>Garcia Bustillos</PERSON> recalled that President-elect <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> views 
the theory of social justice as the basis for international 
relations, and he said this theory should go into effect in 
today's international community. 
  <PERSON>Garcia Bustillos</PERSON> favored <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>'s reintegration into the <ORGANIZATION>OAS</ORGANIZATION> 
as 
part of the family comprising all of the states in the 
continent, and discussed the situation and the recent economic 
measures implemented in <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>. 
  <PERSON>Garcia Bustillos</PERSON> said he met with President-elect <PERSON>Caldera</PERSON> to 
exchange general views regarding foreign policy. 

</TEXT>

