</HEADER>

<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Announces New Cabinet Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Announces New Cabinet Reshuffle </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2805201294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1920 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2805201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Caracas</LOCATION>, 28 <DATE>May</DATE> (EFE) -- Today, the <ORGANIZATION>Venezuelan 
Government</ORGANIZATION> announced a series of changes in President <PERSON>Rafael 
Caldera</PERSON>'s cabinet. These changes are designed to improve 
coherence in the government team. According to <PERSON>Guillermo 
Alvarez</PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION>Central Information Office</ORGANIZATION>, the new 
development minister will be <PERSON>Alberto Poletto</PERSON>, president of the 
<ORGANIZATION>Foreign Trade Institute</ORGANIZATION> [ICE]. Poletto will continue to be 
president of the ICE, and in the future, this office will become 
the ministry of industry and commerce. 
  Luis <PERSON>Carlos Palacios</PERSON>, the current development minister, will 
head the <ORGANIZATION>Central Office of Coordination and Planning</ORGANIZATION>. Palacios 
will replace <PERSON>Enzo del Bufalo</PERSON> who, according to the press, 
resigned because of serious differences with the other members 
of the economic cabinet. 
  <PERSON>Ciro Zaa</PERSON>, currently minister of urban development, has been 
appointed transport and communications minister. Zaa replaces 
<PERSON>Cesar Quintini</PERSON> who was accused of not being willing to attack 
the corruption spotted in the department by former <ORGANIZATION>Deputy 
Transport and Communications</ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON>Rafael Iribarren</PERSON>. 
  <PERSON>Francisco Gonzalez</PERSON>, currently president of the <ORGANIZATION>Urban 
Development Fund</ORGANIZATION>, will replace <PERSON>Ciro Zaa</PERSON> as the new minister of 
urban development. The <ORGANIZATION>Urban Development Fund</ORGANIZATION> will shortly come 
under the <ORGANIZATION>Urban Development Ministry</ORGANIZATION>. 
  One of the changes that surprised all the local political 
observers took place in the Venezuelan Investment Fund, 
responsible for the privatization process. <PERSON>Abdon Vivas Teran</PERSON>, 
head of the Venezuelan Investment Fund, has been replaced by 
<PERSON>Carlos Bernardez</PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Venezuela</ORGANIZATION>, 
the oldest private bank in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>. 
  The chief of the <ORGANIZATION>Central Information Office</ORGANIZATION> also announced 
that <PERSON>Alfredo Gruber</PERSON> will be the new president of the <ORGANIZATION>Venezuelan 
Guayana Corporation</ORGANIZATION>, the most powerful state-run business group. 
<PERSON>Gruber</PERSON> will replace <PERSON>Francisco Layrisse</PERSON> who, a few days ago, 
announced that he wishes to return to private practice. 
  The latest addition to the cabinet, announced today, has 
been 
the appointment of <PERSON>Pompeyo Marquez</PERSON>, currently a minister without 
portfolio, as coordinator for the government's social programs. 
The new members of the cabinet will be sworn in on <DATE>Monday</DATE> [30 
<DATE>May</DATE>] and will start to work immediately, <PERSON>Alvarez</PERSON> said. 

</TEXT>

