</HEADER>

<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Caldera Receives Portuguese Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caldera Receives Portuguese Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1806140894 Caracas EL NACIONAL in Spanish 17 Jun 94 p A-2 </F>
<F P=103> PA1806140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas EL NACIONAL </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Josefina Blanco</PERSON>] </F>
  [Text] A warm afternoon and a superb view of <LOCATION>Mount Avila</LOCATION> 
greeted Portuguese Prime Minister <PERSON>Anibal Cavaco Silva</PERSON>. A UH-214 
<ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> helicopter took the Portuguese premier and his entourage 
from the <LOCATION>Maiquetia Airport</LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION>General Francisco de Miranda 
Air Base</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>La Carlota</LOCATION>. The group included Foreign Minister 
<PERSON>Jose Durao Barroso</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Commerce</ORGANIZATION> and Tourism Minister <PERSON>Fernando Faria 
de Oliveira</PERSON>, and <PERSON>Luis Sousa de Macedo</PERSON>, secretary of state for 
Portuguese communities. 
  Venezuelan President <PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON> received the 
distinguished party with words that recalled the long and close 
relations between both countries and the beneficial presence of 
the large Portuguese community in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>: "....the Portuguese 
presence in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> has without doubt proved to be very 
positive," the Venezuelan president said. Both leaders met at 
the recent Ibero-American Summit held in <LOCATION>Cartagena de Indias</LOCATION>, 
<LOCATION>Colombia</LOCATION>, at the beginning of this week. 
  The Venezuelan reception committee included Foreign Minister 
<PERSON>Miguel Angel Burelli</PERSON>, Tourism Minister <PERSON>Herman Luis Soriano</PERSON>, and 
Armed Forces Commander <PERSON>Otto Garcia</PERSON>. 
  Upon his arrival, <PERSON>Cavaco Silva</PERSON>, who is 54 years old, has a 
degree in finance, is a professor and member of the Social 
Democratic party (PSD), and is visiting this country for the 
first time, highlighted the importance of his four-day mission 
in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>. He comes, he said, to strengthen the existing 
political, cultural, economic, and business relations between 
both countries. The head of the Portuguese nation said he was 
accompanied by 50 of the most important and significant 
businessmen in his country. 
  <PERSON>Cavaco Silva</PERSON> also said that he visited the country as a 
member of the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>) and that the talks would thus 
cover the strengthening of relations between the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION> and the 
Latin American countries, taking into account the fact that 
<LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> has played an important role in furthering integration 
in the region. 
  <PERSON>Cavaco Silva</PERSON>'s presence in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> will seal three 
cooperation agreements between both countries. One is a two-way 
investment and protection agreement, another will cover the 
prevention, control, and surveillance of drug use, and the third 
is for technical cooperation in several fields such as 
agriculture, fisheries, tourism, and maritime transportation. 

</TEXT>

